---
/**
 * context-engineering 0002 · Figure 4 — "ranking vs re-ranking — two jobs".
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from
 * docs/context-engineering/lessons/0002-context-selection-and-retrieval.html
 * (figure + svg + figcaption incl. the footnote <sup>). It lives as an .astro
 * component, NOT inline in the MDX, because MDX's JSX parser is unreliable with
 * raw inline SVG that uses kebab-case attributes.
 *
 * The source page defined the arrowhead markers ONCE in a shared <defs> block at
 * the top of the document <body>. The only marker this figure references (arwM)
 * is inlined into its own <defs>.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 600 180"
        role="img"
        aria-label="Stage one ranking optimizes recall across many; stage two re-ranking optimizes precision on the top few."
    >
        <defs>
            <marker
                id="arwM"
                viewBox="0 0 10 10"
                refX="8.5"
                refY="5"
                markerWidth="7"
                markerHeight="7"
                orient="auto-start-reverse"
                ><path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 z" fill="#b5179e"></path></marker
            >
        </defs>
        <text x="150" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#1f3a5a"
            >Ranking (stage 1)</text
        >
        <text x="450" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >Re-ranking (stage 2)</text
        >

        <rect x="40" y="34" width="220" height="118" rx="8" fill="#eef2f7" stroke="#1f3a5a"></rect>
        <text x="150" y="56" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#6b675f"
            >cheap score · many candidates</text
        >
        <text x="150" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#1f3a5a"
            >optimize RECALL</text
        >
        <text x="150" y="96" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#6b675f"
            >&ldquo;don't miss the right doc&rdquo;</text
        >
        <text x="150" y="122" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#111110"
            >BM25 score · cosine score</text
        >
        <text x="150" y="138" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#111110"
            >applied to the whole net</text
        >

        <rect x="340" y="34" width="220" height="118" rx="8" fill="#efe7f0" stroke="#111110"></rect>
        <text x="450" y="56" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#6b675f"
            >expensive score · top-N only</text
        >
        <text x="450" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >optimize PRECISION</text
        >
        <text x="450" y="96" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#6b675f"
            >&ldquo;put the best at the top&rdquo;</text
        >
        <text x="450" y="122" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#111110"
            >cross-encoder · query+doc jointly</text
        >
        <text x="450" y="138" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#111110"
            >large precision lift on the top</text
        >

        <line
            x1="262"
            y1="93"
            x2="338"
            y2="93"
            stroke="#b5179e"
            stroke-dasharray="4 3"
            marker-end="url(#arwM)"></line>
        <text x="300" y="86" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" font-weight="700" fill="#b5179e"
            >top-N</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        First stage is wide and cheap to buy recall; second stage is narrow and expensive to buy
        precision. The cross-encoder reads query and document together, so it scores relevance far
        more accurately — but only on what stage 1 handed it.<sup><a href="#s4" id="r4b">4</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
